`This element is used in the <LongTitle\> only. It is used to control the case of the first letter of the long title. On Page 1 of a Bill the first letter must be in upper case, whilst on the endorsement (back page) it must be in lower case. It is necessary to update the endorsement\qs element definitions to set the case correctly.'

`The <Origin\> element is used in predominantly consolidated Bills. These are Bills which are made up of a number of other Bills (i.e. they are consolidated). ElementDef.EDComments: `Used to determine where multiple-volume Bills should be divided into separate books. Splitting can occur anywhere within the Part/Chapter/CrossHeading structure of the clauses, or between Schedules. A split will never occur within a Schedule. Typically the split is only required for long Bills (e.g. Fincance Bill) where there is a physical limit to the number of pages that can be stapled by the printer. Mekon\qs FDK plugin actually allows for multiple splits, however, this will never really be more than 2 volumes.'

ElementDef.EDComments: `This element was called <InternalReference\> in Release 33 and below. It was changed to <Xref\> as it was becoming more widely used to create cross references between files.'
`This element is used to create cross references to <Chapter\> elements within the Bill book. Upon concatenation they are converted into regular <Xref\> elements.'

`The <DummyXref\> element is used within House amendments to indicate where a cross reference would be required when it is introduced into the Bill text. It is not intended for use within Bill text only.'
`This element is used to create cross references to <Part\> elements within the Bill book. Upon concatenation they are converted into regular <Xref\> elements.'
